(39, 'Registered Education Savings Plans', 'Financial', '<p class="new-customtext">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<center>\r\n<h5 style="box-sizing: border-box; font-family: Raleway; font-weight: 700; line-height: 24px; color: rgb(5, 70, 0); margin: 0px 0px 15px; font-size: 18px; font-style: normal;">Introduction to the Canadian Education Savings Plan</h5>\r\n</center>\r\nRegistered Education Savings Plans (RESP, referred to in the Chinese community is commonly referred to as the &quot;Education Fund&quot;) is the Canadian government based on the income tax law (Income Tax Act) set up to encourage parents to accept their future university or college education And a subsidy program for savings.\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="new-customtext">According to the plan, parents can earn up to $ 4,000 per child per year and a maximum of $ 42,000 for a lifetime. Among them, the government provides 20% of the subsidy for the parent&#39;s annual savings of $ 2,000, or $ 400, which is called the Canada Education Savings Grant (CESG). The government gives each child an educational savings scholarship up to $ 7,200 in life. Although RESP can not apply for tax credits at the time of filing with the Registered Retirement Savings Plan (RRSP), the benefits of savings in the RESP program and CESG investments are tax-free.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="new-customtext">RESP has many advantages for parents who have children: first, parents earn $ 2,000 per year and government subsidies $ 400, which is equivalent to 20% return on investment. For low- or middle-income families, parents earn $ 2,000 a year and government subsidies are $ 500, equivalent to 25% return on investment.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="new-customtext">Second, the savings of the parents can be invested in different projects (eg, GICs, mutual funds, etc.), as long as they are within the RESP limit ($ 4,000 per year), and their investment income (and compound interest growth) is tax-free, We do not need to report as taxation income of parent. All investment income is taxable only as income when the child is used. Because the child as a student does not, or rarely have other income, so this part of the investment income can actually be said to be tax-free. This is very different from the investment or savings in the RESP program, and the proceeds of your savings or investment are taxed as required. Finally, even if the child can not continue to have higher education for some reason in the future, the parent&#39;s savings and investment income can be retrieved (of course, the CESG scholarship is refundable to the government).<br style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;" />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="new-customtext">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h4 class="new-customtext"><strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">The contents of the registered educational savings plan</strong></h4>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="new-customtext">It is easy to start a savings plan. You can start a family or personal savings plan with a minimum of $ 500 or a monthly contribution of at least $ 25. An annual contribution of $ 2,000 or $ 4,000 and a lifetime contribution of $ 42,000. The annual contribution deadline is December 31. If you add a new child, just add your name to the list of beneficiaries or start another new savings plan.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="new-customtext">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h4 class="new-customtext"><strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Extra offer</strong></h4>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="new-customtext">The Government of Canada, through the Canadian Education Savings Subsidy Fund (CESG), provides additional grants for each child&#39;s savings plan until they are 18 years old. Each child earns up to $ 400/800 or a maximum of $ 7,200 per year (20% * $ 2000 = $ 400 * 18 years = $ 7,200.) If you are unable to contribute to the maximum contribution limit of $ 2,000 in a given year Unused contribution limits can be left for future use (up to $ 800 accumulated grants). Your child must have a Social Security number (SIN) to qualify for a grant.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="new-customtext">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h4 class="new-customtext"><strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Tax concessions</strong></h4>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="new-customtext">Unlike the Registered Retirement Savings (RRSP), the Registered Education Savings Scheme (RESP) can not be used for tax cuts. But the amount accumulated in the plan can be taxed before your child is admitted to college or university. When withdrawals are required to pay for educational expenses (such as tuition, books, accommodation, transportation, etc.), the tax payable should be calculated on the basis of the income, not the original contribution. In general, because beneficiaries are still income-free or low-income students, their rates are usually lower. Therefore, the income tax payable should be very few.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="new-customtext">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h4 class="new-customtext"><strong style="margin: 0px; padding: 0px;">Double discount</strong></h4>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="new-customtext">If one of your children does not intend to enter any college or university before the age of 21, your other child can be a matter of course to become the beneficiaries of the plan. In case you do not have any children who wish to continue your studies, you can choose to withdraw your money from your contribution or benefit, or transfer your planned income to your personal or spouse-registered retirement savings plan. The following conditions apply: * There are remaining payment limits in the RRSP, and the maximum amount of transfers is $ 50.000.)</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="new-customtext">The benefits of investing in RESP</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="new-customtext">1, investment in the investment income in the RESP as long as the reservation on the account will not be taxed</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="new-customtext">2, the establishment of the RESP, the Canadian government will be based on your annual contribution, give you 20% of education savings subsidies, life-long up to $ 7,200 grant</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="new-customtext">3. The amount of RESP that is withdrawn at any time is not taxable (excluding investment income)</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="new-customtext">4. If a child is unwilling to receive a higher education, the beneficiary can be changed to another child</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="new-customtext">5. Under certain conditions, RESP can be transferred to RRSP</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="new-customtext">6. The amount invested in RESP can be used as collateral for other loans</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n', '', '', 'Registered Education Savings Plans', 1, 0),
(40, 'Insurance', 'Financial', '<div class="service-block col-sm-4 col-xs-6"><img alt="service" class="sppb-img-responsive" src="/images/insurance/1.jpg" /> <a href="contact.php?insurance=1" target="_parent"> </a>\r\n\r\n<h3 class="title"><a href="contact.php?insurance=1" target="_parent">Auto-Car Insurance</a></h3>\r\n<a href="contact.php?insurance=1" target="_parent"> </a>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<a class="simple" href="contact.php?insurance=1" target="_parent">Learn more </a></div>\r\n\r\n<div class="service-block col-sm-4 col-xs-6"><img alt="service" class="sppb-img-responsive" src="/images/services/2.jpg" /> <a href="contact.php?insurance=1" target="_parent"> </a>\r\n\r\n<h3 class="title"><a href="contact.php?insurance=1" target="_parent">Home Insurance</a></h3>\r\n<a href="contact.php?insurance=1" target="_parent"> </a>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<a class="simple" href="contact.php?insurance=1" target="_parent">Learn more </a></div>\r\n\r\n<div class="service-block col-sm-4 col-xs-6"><img alt="service" class="sppb-img-responsive" src="/images/services/3.jpg" /> <a href="contact.php?insurance=1" target="_parent"> </a>\r\n\r\n<h3 class="title"><a href="contact.php?insurance=1" target="_parent">Term Life Insurance</a></h3>\r\n<a href="contact.php?insurance=1" target="_parent"> </a>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<a class="simple" href="contact.php?insurance=1" target="_parent">Learn more </a></div>\r\n\r\n<div class="service-block col-sm-4 col-xs-6"><img alt="service" class="sppb-img-responsive" src="/images/services/4.jpg" /> <a href="contact.php?insurance=1" target="_parent"> </a>\r\n\r\n<h3 class="title"><a href="contact.php?insurance=1" target="_parent">Medical Insurance</a></h3>\r\n<a href="contact.php?insurance=1" target="_parent"> </a>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<a class="simple" href="contact.php?insurance=1" target="_parent">Learn more </a></div>\r\n\r\n<div class="service-block col-sm-4 col-xs-6"><img alt="service" class="sppb-img-responsive" src="/images/services/5.jpg" /> <a href="contact.php?insurance=1" target="_parent"> </a>\r\n\r\n<h3 class="title"><a href="contact.php?insurance=1" target="_parent">Travel Insurance</a></h3>\r\n<a href="contact.php?insurance=1" target="_parent"> </a>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<a class="simple" href="contact.php?insurance=1" target="_parent">Learn more </a></div>\r\n\r\n<div class="service-block col-sm-4 col-xs-6"><img alt="service" class="sppb-img-responsive" src="/images/services/6.jpg" /> <a href="#" target="_parent"> </a>\r\n\r\n<h3 class="title"><a href="#" target="_parent">FAQ</a></h3>\r\n<a href="#" target="_parent"> </a>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<a class="simple" href="insurance-faq.php" target="_parent">Learn more </a></div>\r\n', '', '', 'Insurance', 1, 0),
(41, 'Insurance FAQ', 'Financial', '<p>What is the most important thing to watch in life insurance?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;<br />\r\nIn the process of purchasing life insurance, mainland migrants often focus on comparing the prices of different companies&#39; products. But in reality, a professional integrity and customer needs to be placed in the first consideration of the broker, far more than the price of different companies is more important. Ontario life insurance license test book also said: because the market competition so that different insurance companies similar insurance products, the price difference is very small and other reasons, if a broker can professional analysis of the actual needs of the insured, the interests of the insured Before the broker&#39;s own interests, the insured usually does not have to need shopping around. We also found in practice that the insurance products purchased if the problem, the biggest problem is often not bought the company&#39;s product problems, but such as insurance types and insurance Whether the amount is in line with the needs of the insured, whether the premium is reasonable, whether the broker recommends the product or the recommended practice is honest and so on</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>After the purchase is to buy mortgage insurance or regular life insurance is good?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;<br />\r\n&nbsp;<br />\r\nWhen you buy a house loan or redo your home loan, someone may recommend you to buy a house (mortgage) loan insurance. But before the purchase, to deal with other possible options to do some further understanding. In general, regular life insurance has the following advantages over housing mortgage insurance: the vast majority of cases are cheaper than mortgage insurance; the insured amount does not decrease with the amount of loan repayment; the beneficiary of the insured person is the family of the insured person Not a loan unit, so once the insured person something, his family can directly get and control compensation funds. If you have already purchased a mortgage insurance, you may wish to do a comparison of inquiries, because such insurance can be replaced at any time, there will be no loss.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I am ready to return to China later, in Canada or in China to buy insurance is good?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;<br />\r\nOf course in Canada. First, because Canada&#39;s life expectancy is much higher than China, and second, the Canadian insurance company&#39;s operation has been more than 100 years of history, management has been more mature, so its insurance price is much lower than China. Similar insurance in Canada is only about one-fourth of the insurance price in China. In fact, the price of China&#39;s life insurance is not only far higher than Canada, but also higher than Hong Kong. A few years before the provisions permit, there have been many Hong Kong insurance brokers to the mainland to sell insurance products. Therefore, if your identity can be purchased in Canada, life insurance and serious illness insurance, before leaving Canada should be considered in Canada to do such a plan.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I am ready to return to China later, in Canada to buy insurance in the future claims a problem?<br />\r\nno problem. First, as long as the purchase of insurance policy in line with the requirements of the insurance company, after the issuance of the policy no matter how the insured person to change the identity of residence or nationality (such as abandon the Canadian identity), the policy is not affected. Second, the Canadian insurance company recognized the world&#39;s police, funeral home, or hospital issued by the death certificate. If the death certificate is not in English or French, the original and English or French translations are required. In fact, our customers have died in Hong Kong, issued by the Hong Kong funeral home death certificate, sent to the insurance company in Canada and claims.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Someone suggested that I invested a lot of money every year to the policy, so okay?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;<br />\r\nThe main function of insurance is to protect, investment is only by-product. So the annual investment in life insurance funds generally should not exceed 7-8% of income. From the perspective of investment, lifetime insurance for children is often used because of the low cost and long investment time, even if the annual funding ratio is low. But the age of 30 years old or even greater people, if you want to retire when the policy has a considerable cash pension, only now to the policy into the high capital. In this case the insured person should consider whether the future also need to buy a house and other large expenses, whether the child&#39;s university education costs such as RESP plan has been arranged, whether the purchase of RRSP funds have been considered, whether to determine no other better or scattered risk The direction of investment and so on. In addition, since the Government has a maximum limit on the amount of investment in the policy, it is necessary to raise the amount of insurance when it is necessary to invest in high funds. It should also be determined that the amount paid is not more than their actual needs.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>How much do I buy insurance every year to buy insurance is reasonable?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;<br />\r\nFor the vast majority of wage earners, our proposal is within 7-8% of household income, not more than this percentage. Except for the exception, of course, if you have not found a new immigrant job, you should make a monthly 20-30 yuan to buy a regular insurance. And some more people who have more savings may be higher than the percentage or even after the immigration has not yet stabilized before the income to buy a larger insurance, but this is only a few cases. A small number of insurance brokers encourage the insured to put a large portion of their income into insurance each year. But this is generally not a reasonable recommendation, should be careful. Especially new immigrants, later also buy a house, children read the university, their pension, all money. In fact, such as Ontario in the insurance broker license examination materials have to buy life insurance expenses, should be in the family income of about 7-8% of the proposal. Therefore, for a broker, this should be common sense.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you buy insurance to fill in the information is not what the consequences?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;<br />\r\nWhen applying for insurance, the insured must fill in the information must be correct. If something is found afterwards, you should declare a correction to the insurance company. In the event of a false claim or concealment of information by an insurer&#39;s investigation, it may have different results depending on the degree of false or hidden information. If the age is wrong, conceal the fact that smoking, etc., the insurance company will be based on the correct age or smoking facts to re-calculate the premium paid by the insured, and then deduct the difference from the amount of premiums. But if it is to conceal the insured person&#39;s personal history, etc., may lead to insurance companies refuse to compensate.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Someone to buy insurance for children, what is the point?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;<br />\r\nTo buy insurance for children, mainly from the investment point of view. The investment significance of life insurance is mainly reflected in three aspects, one is duty-free value-added, especially in the future of older children in the larger value of the cash value is relatively large, the second is the regular accumulation of savings; Third, for children, due to a long investment, late value-added is very significant. Specifically, Manulife&#39;s 2005 product, for example, purchased 250,000 whole live life for a five-year-old boy with an annual contribution of $ 813 and a death benefit of $ 1,571,443 at the age of 65, surrender Cash value is $ 703,443; death compensation at age 80 is $ 2,878,834 and cash is available at $ 1,889,857. Obviously a reward for the pen. Of course, this is based on the current company&#39;s dividend standard calculation, the future can also get so much, depending on the future dividends, can not guarantee. But one is such insurance plan investment risk is not large, the second is what investment is completely risk-free yet it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Some people say that buying regular insurance is enough, there is no need to buy life, right?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;<br />\r\nPeriodic insurance is characterized by cheap and only limited period of time. So if the economy is not well-off and need insurance, or the purpose is only for a certain period of time within the protection, may consider buying only regular insurance. But that does not mean that even if the economic conditions permit, there is no need to buy life insurance. First of all from a cost-effective point of view, assuming a 40-year-old non-smoking physical condition of the middle of the men to buy 25 million insurance to Manulife 2005 products, for example, 20 years a monthly premium of $ 39.05, universal life life insurance The monthly premium is $ 119.71.60 when the total amount of premium paid is 20 years paid $ 9372, UL insurance paid $ 28,730. If the age of 60 passed away, of course, is to buy regular cost-effective. But if the 60 years after the death of life insurance is a cost-effective. Even when the average life expectancy of men in Canada 78 years old, UL paid a total of $ 54,587 premium, but after all, can eventually get back 250,000, unlike the regular insurance, there is no life expectancy on nothing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nSecondly, from the insurance needs, not the housing loans, children&#39;s college graduates and other regular security outside there is no insurance needs. Others, such as their own after the death of the spouse there is not enough life and pension costs, burial costs, etc. also need children after adult still need to protect the plan. If this time is still a temporary insurance alternative, one is 60 years of age after the regular insurance is also very expensive (such as the men&#39;s 60-year-old renewal, 25 million Canadian dollars 20 years of regular insurance, the monthly premium is $ 247.71, Age of the above-mentioned UL life insurance is more than doubled), the second is the regular insurance until only 75 years old. In addition, if there are personal assets, after the death may involve tax, asset transfer, lawyers accountants and other expenses need insurance funds to protect the assets. So from the perspective of asset protection may also need insurance.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What is a flexible investment life insurance (Universal Life Insurance)? What are the main features?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;<br />\r\nFlexible investment-type life insurance is the same as a dividend-based life insurance, as well as a permanent life insurance. The difference between the two is that the flexible investment-based life insurance investment premium investment part of the investment direction is the risk of different funds, and the insured person according to their own wishes and risk-taking ability to choose the direction of investment and fund type, rather than Like the dividend type of life insurance by the insurance company to invest in the direction of the insured only to participate in dividends. So the insured in the direction of investment can choose a personal choice, but at the same time bear the risk of investment.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What is bonus life life insurance (Whole Life Insurance)? What are the main features?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;<br />\r\nDividend Life Insurance is one of Life Life Insurance. Its characteristics: First, the insured will eventually get a sum of insurance compensation. If the insured person died before a hundred years old, the person will receive the insurance amount plus the investment compensation; if the insured person is still alive at one hundred years old, the insurance company will insure the investment directly to the insured Own oneself. Second, the insured pay premium is divided into two parts, part of the insurance costs, part of the investment part. Its investment part of the investment direction and management by the insurance company unified supervision, insured participation in dividends. So the insured person died or over a hundred years of age when the amount of compensation, as a result of the increase in investment, it is generally higher than the insurance.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What is Term Life Insurance? What are the main features?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;<br />\r\nPeriodic life insurance is an insurance that guarantees death within a specified insured period. According to the insured period can be divided into: 10 years on a regular basis, 20 years on a regular basis, and to 100 years of age three. The first two are within the insured period if there is no life accident, the insurance will also have no compensation or compensation at the end of the termination, so the premium is relatively cheap, suitable for temporary security needs. The latter is actually the same as life insurance, if the insured person has not been a hundred years of life accident, will also receive insurance compensation. Another feature of regular insurance is that premiums do not contain any investment, so the insured will not add value. Such as buying 250,000 regular insurance, any period of life within the insured life accident, the compensation is 250,000, no more.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p>What is the need to buy life insurance in Canada? What are the main types of life insurance?</p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;<br />\r\nWhether a person needs to buy life insurance, financial planning should mainly consider the following factors: the spouse&#39;s life and pension costs; minor children&#39;s living expenses, spouses and children&#39;s education costs; housing loans and other debt; emergency and final expenses etc. Last Expenses are the last expenses before and after a person&#39;s death. If the family is earning earners, the final cost will be the first consideration for the family. This includes: the final medical expenses; burial fees; bills for families and their individuals; loans from banks and other units; installment debts; unpaid land tax; costs involved in estate rehousing and transfer; and various types of final taxes. In addition, we Chinese people have the tradition of supporting the elderly, if you need your old life support, in the purchase of life insurance also need to consider.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br />\r\nCanada Life Insurance covers life insurance (Term Life Insurance) and life insurance (permanent life insurance) two categories. Regular and 10 years on a regular basis, 20 years on a regular basis and to 100 years of age three. In addition, there are two more special regular life insurance, one is the housing mortgage insurance, the second is the group insurance. Lifetime Life Insurance is divided into Life Life Insurance (Life Insurance, or called Participating Life Insurance) and flexible investment life insurance (Universal Life Insurance, or called Non-under Life Insurance)</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="p" style="margin-top: 0.0000pt; margin-right: 0.0000pt; margin-bottom: 7.5000pt; margin-left: 0.0000pt; padding: 0pt 0pt 0pt 0pt; mso-pagination: widow-orphan; line-height: 16.5000pt;">。<o:p></o:p></p>\r\n\r\n<p class="MsoNormal"><o:p> &nbsp;</o:p></p>\r\n', '', '', 'Insurance FAQ', 1, 0),
(42, 'Calculator', 'apply', '<div class="col-md-4">\r\n<table class="table">\r\n	<caption class="bg-success">\r\n	<center>\r\n	<h4><b>Latest rates</b></h4>\r\n	</center>\r\n	</caption>\r\n	<thead>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<th>#</th>\r\n			<th>Term</th>\r\n			<th>Bank Rate</th>\r\n			<th>Our Rate</th>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</thead>\r\n	<tbody>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<th scope="row">1</th>\r\n			<td>1 year</td>\r\n			<td>3.09</td>\r\n			<td>2.19</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<th scope="row">2</th>\r\n			<td>2 year</td>\r\n			<td>3.04</td>\r\n			<td>1.99</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<th scope="row">3</th>\r\n			<td>3 year</td>\r\n			<td>3.75</td>\r\n			<td>2.19</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<th scope="row">4</th>\r\n			<td>4 year</td>\r\n			<td>3.94</td>\r\n			<td>2.44</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n		<tr>\r\n			<th scope="row">5</th>\r\n			<td>5 year</td>\r\n			<td>4.79</td>\r\n			<td>2.34</td>\r\n		</tr>\r\n	</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div class="col-md-8">\r\n<h4 class="new-customtext">What will your monthly payment be?</h4>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<form name="first">\r\n<div class="form-group row"><label class="col-sm-2 col-form-label">Mortgage Amount:</label>\r\n\r\n<div class="col-sm-6 input-group"><span class="input-group-addon">$</span> <input class="form-control" name="aa" onkeyup="checnum(this)" type="text" /></div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div class="form-group row"><label class="col-sm-2 col-form-label">Amortization Period(year):</label>\r\n\r\n<div class="col-sm-6 input-group"><input class="form-control" name="cc" onkeyup="checnum(this)" type="text" /> <span class="input-group-addon">Year</span></div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div class="form-group row"><label class="col-sm-2 col-form-label">Interest Rate:</label>\r\n\r\n<div class="col-sm-6 input-group"><input class="form-control" name="bb" onkeyup="checnum(this)" type="text" /> <span class="input-group-addon">%</span></div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div class="form-group row">\r\n<div class="col-sm-6"><input class="form-control" name="ss" onclick="loan()" type="button" value="Calculate" /></div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<h4 class="new-customtext">EST Result：</h4>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<div class="form-group row"><label class="col-sm-2 col-form-label">Monthly Payment:</label>\r\n\r\n<div class="col-sm-6"><input class="form-control" name="r1" readonly="readonly" type="text" /></div>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n<div class="form-group row"><label class="col-sm-2 col-form-label">Monthly Interest:</label>\r\n\r\n<div class="col-sm-6"><input class="form-control" name="r3" readonly="readonly" type="text" /></div>\r\n</div>\r\n</form>\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n', '        </section>\r\n				<script type="text/javascript">\r\n					function checnum(as)\r\n					{\r\n					var dd = as.value;\r\n					if(isNaN(dd))\r\n					{\r\n					dd = dd.substring(0,(dd.length-1));\r\n					as.value = dd;\r\n					}\r\n					} function loan() {\r\n					var a = document.first.aa.value;\r\n					var b = document.first.bb.value;\r\n					var c = document.first.cc.value;\r\n					var n = c * 12;\r\n					var t = (b/200)+1 ;\r\n\r\n					var r = Math.pow(t,1/6)-1;\r\n\r\n					var p = (a * r *Math.pow((1+r),n))/(Math.pow((1+r),n)-1);\r\n					var prin = Math.round(p*100)/100;\r\n\r\n					document.first.r1.value = prin;\r\n					var mon = Math.round(((n * prin) - a)*100)/100;\r\n\r\n					var tot = Math.round((mon/n)*100)/100;\r\n					document.first.r3.value = tot;\r\n					for(var i=0;i<n;i++)\r\n					{\r\n					var z = a * r * 1;\r\n					var q = Math.round(z*100)/100;\r\n					var t = p - z;\r\n					var w = Math.round(t*100)/100;\r\n					var e = a-t;\r\n					var l = Math.round(e*100)/100;\r\n					a=e;\r\n					}\r\n					 }\r\n\r\n					</script>', '', 'Calculator', 1, 0),
(43, 'FAQ', 'apply', '<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class="new-customtext">Should I get pre-approved for a mortgage before I start looking for a house?</h3>\r\n<span class="new-customtext">Getting pre-approved for a mortgage should be one of the first steps you take when buying a new home. By doing so, you&rsquo;ll know how much the bank is willing to lend you and, therefore, how much you can afford when shopping for your new home. Pre-approval will tell you what your expected mortgage payments will be. You may also be able to lock in your interest rate at the current rate to protect you from the potential of rising interest rates.</span>\r\n\r\n<p class="new-customtext">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="new-customtext">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class="new-customtext">What is a rate guarantee?</h3>\r\n<span class="new-customtext">An interest rate guarantee allows you to lock in your interest rate at the current rate for a certain period of time. This allows you to shop for your new home knowing what your interest rate and payments will be, without worrying about whether rising interest rates will affect how much you can afford. For Manulife Bank Select, we&rsquo;ll guarantee the interest rate that was in effect on the date of your application for 90 days if you are purchasing a resale home and 120 days if you are purchasing a new construction home. If the rate in effect on the day your home purchase closes is lower, you will receive the better rate.</span>\r\n\r\n<p class="new-customtext">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="new-customtext">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class="new-customtext">What is the difference between short and long term mortgages? What are the benefits of each?</h3>\r\n<span class="new-customtext">Mortgages are available in terms of different lengths; 1 to 5 year, 7 and 10 year terms are the most common. Interest rates on shorter-term mortgages are typically lower than those of longer-term mortgages due to several factors, such as: the interest rates the lenders pay on client deposits which are then lent out via mortgages, lines of credit, etc., along with administrative costs and general economic factors which are more predictable in the shorter term. Short and long-term mortgages each have their own benefits depending on your individual situation, personal preferences and comfort level. If you think rates may drop in the near future, you may choose a short-term mortgage in the hopes of taking advantage of lower rates when your term ends. If you think interest rates are going to rise, you may choose a fixed-rate, longer-term mortgage to secure a lower rate that you can count on for payments that suit your comfort level. It&rsquo;s also possible that over the longer term, the fixed rate may end up being lower than the effective interest rate of shorter terms renewing over that time period.</span>\r\n\r\n<p class="new-customtext">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="new-customtext">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<h3 class="new-customtext">What are the monthly expenses associated with owning a home?</h3>\r\n<span class="new-customtext">In addition to your mortgage costs, you should also be prepared for the monthly expenses that go along with owning your own home. Some typical monthly expenses to be aware of include hydro, utilities, phone and cable, maintenance costs, home insurance, mortgage life insurance, property taxes and condo fees (if applicable). When you&rsquo;re budgeting for your mortgage costs, be sure that you have enough income left over to cover these monthly expenses.</span>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n', '', '', 'FAQ', 1, 0),
